## ⚛️ React

### 🔹 Core Concepts

#### ❓ What is the Virtual DOM?

- [ ] A. A copy of the real DOM stored in the browser
- [ ] B. A lightweight in-memory representation of the DOM
- [ ] C. A database of UI elements
- [ ] D. A CSS abstraction

<details>
<summary>✅ Answer</summary>

**B. A lightweight in-memory representation of the DOM**

React keeps a virtual DOM in memory and syncs it with the real DOM using a process called reconciliation. This avoids expensive direct DOM manipulations by batching and diffing changes first.

</details>

---

#### ❓ What is reconciliation in React?

- [ ] A. Merging two Redux stores
- [ ] B. The process of comparing old and new virtual DOM trees to update the real DOM
- [ ] C. A lifecycle method
- [ ] D. Fetching remote data and syncing it to state

<details>
<summary>✅ Answer</summary>

**B. The process of comparing old and new virtual DOM trees to update the real DOM**

React's reconciler (formerly called the "diff algorithm", now Fiber-based) compares the previous and new virtual DOM trees and applies only the minimal set of changes needed.

</details>

---

#### ❓ What is React Fiber?

- [ ] A. A CSS-in-JS library
- [ ] B. A network request manager in React
- [ ] C. React's internal reconciliation engine that enables incremental rendering
- [ ] D. A deprecated feature replaced by hooks

<details>
<summary>✅ Answer</summary>

**C. React's internal reconciliation engine that enables incremental rendering**

React Fiber (introduced in React 16) is a complete rewrite of the reconciler. It enables features like time-slicing, Suspense, and concurrent rendering by breaking rendering work into small units that can be paused and resumed.

</details>

