#### ❓ What is `useCallback` used for?

- [ ] A. Memoizing a computed value
- [ ] B. Memoizing a function reference so it does not get recreated on every render
- [ ] C. Replacing `useState`
- [ ] D. Scheduling asynchronous work

<details>
<summary>✅ Answer</summary>

**B. Memoizing a function reference so it does not get recreated on every render**

`useCallback` returns a stable function reference that only changes when its dependencies change. Useful when passing callbacks to child components wrapped in `React.memo`.

</details>

---

#### ❓ What is `useMemo` used for?

- [ ] A. Memoizing a function definition
- [ ] B. Caching the result of an expensive computation between renders
- [ ] C. Managing async state
- [ ] D. Setting global state

<details>
<summary>✅ Answer</summary>

**B. Caching the result of an expensive computation between renders**

`useMemo` recomputes the value only when its dependencies change. It avoids re-running expensive calculations on every render.

</details>

---

#### ❓ What is the difference between `useMemo` and `useCallback`?

- [ ] A. There is no difference
- [ ] B. `useMemo` memoizes a value; `useCallback` memoizes a function
- [ ] C. `useCallback` memoizes a value; `useMemo` memoizes a function
- [ ] D. Both only work with async functions

<details>
<summary>✅ Answer</summary>

**B. `useMemo` memoizes a value; `useCallback` memoizes a function**

`useMemo(() => computeValue(), deps)` returns the cached value. `useCallback(() => fn(), deps)` is equivalent to `useMemo(() => () => fn(), deps)`.

</details>

